SIMPLE: eject
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Eject
<hw>E*ject"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Ejected</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ejecting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>ejectus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>ejicere</ets>; <ets>e</ets> out + <ets>jacere</ets> to throw. See
<er>Jet</er> a shooting forth.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To expel; to
dismiss; to cast forth; to thrust or drive out; to discharge; <as>as, to
<ex>eject</ex> a person from a room; to <ex>eject</ex> a traitor from
the country; to <ex>eject</ex> words from the language.</as></def>
⟦ldquo⟧Eyes <xex>ejecting</xex> flame.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>H.
Brooke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To cast out; to evict; to
dispossess; <as>as, to <ex>eject</ex> tenants from an
estate</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To expel; banish; drive out; discharge; oust;
evict; dislodge; extrude; void.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eject</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Eject
<hw>E"ject</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Eject</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <fld>(Philos.)</fld> <def>An object that is a
conscious or living object, and hence not a direct object, but an
inferred object or act of a subject, not myself; -- a term invented by
W. K. Clifford.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ejecta</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
